Perfect ğŸ‘ Letâ€™s compare @Primary vs @Qualifier in Spring Boot with a real-life example.

ğŸ’¡ @Primary vs @Qualifier
@Primary â†’ Sets a default bean when multiple beans are available.

@Qualifier â†’ Lets you choose exactly which bean you want to inject.

ğŸ”§ Example Setup
1. PaymentService Interface
public interface PaymentService {
    void pay(double amount);
}
2. Two Implementations
Credit Card Payment

import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class CreditCardPaymentService implements PaymentService {
    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid " + amount + " using Credit Card.");
    }
}
UPI Payment (Marked as Primary)

import org.springframework.context.annotation.Primary;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
@Primary
public class UpiPaymentService implements PaymentService {
    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid " + amount + " using UPI.");
    }
}
1ï¸âƒ£ Using @Primary
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController
public class PrimaryExampleController {

    @Autowired
    private PaymentService paymentService;  // No @Qualifier used

    @GetMapping("/payPrimary")
    public String payUsingPrimary() {
        paymentService.pay(500.0);
        return "Payment done with Primary Bean";
    }
}
ğŸ‘‰ Output (because UpiPaymentService is @Primary):

Paid 500.0 using UPI.
2ï¸âƒ£ Using @Qualifier
Now, letâ€™s say you donâ€™t always want UPI, sometimes you want Credit Card explicitly.

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Qualifier;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController
public class QualifierExampleController {

    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("creditCardPaymentService")   // ğŸ‘ˆ Bean name = class name with small first letter
    private PaymentService paymentService;

    @GetMapping("/payQualifier")
    public String payUsingQualifier() {
        paymentService.pay(1000.0);
        return "Payment done with Qualifier Bean";
    }
}
ğŸ‘‰ Output:

Paid 1000.0 using Credit Card.
ğŸª Real-Time Analogy
@Primary â†’ "Default Cash Counter" in a mall. If customer doesnâ€™t specify, go there.

@Qualifier â†’ Customer says: "No, I want to pay specifically at the Credit Card counter."

âœ… Summary
Feature	@Primary	@Qualifier
Usage	Marks a default bean	Selects a specific bean
When to use	If you mostly use one bean but donâ€™t want errors when multiple exist	If you need different beans in different places
Example output	â€œPaid using UPIâ€ (default)	â€œPaid using Credit Cardâ€ (explicit)
ğŸ‘‰ Best Practice:

Use @Primary for a commonly used default implementation.

Use @Qualifier when you need specific control.

